        title: 'Names, identity, and the quiet weight of a label',
        text: "Many parents believe that a name can shape a child's future. The belief is older than the data, but it is not baseless.\n\nA man named Robert Lane gave his sixth son the name Winner and his seventh son the name Loser. Loser went on to a successful career. Winner cycled through trouble and time behind bars. The names did not make the children, but the story is a reminder that labels are easy to misread.\n\nSome parents pick names that are clearly trying to send a message. A mother who named her daughter Temptress, for example, was probably sending one. The girl did not turn out the way the name hinted.\n\nNames are signals, and signals travel. In job markets, in school admissions, in everyday small choices, the name on a paper is the first thing a stranger sees. Amy Williams often gets a softer read than Jasmine Williams, even when the resume is identical. The effect is small for any one person, but it is real across millions of decisions.\n\nA name is more about the parents than about the child. Parents who care enough to choose with care are giving their child an early sign that they are wanted. Parents who pick a name at random are giving a different sign, and that signal lands long before the child can spell it."
